    <div rend="parallel">
      <lg xml:id="TolE0153">
<l>uyirī ṟākiya vuyartiṇaip peyarum</l>
<l>puḷḷi yiṟuti yuyartiṇaip peyaru</l>
<l>mellā vaḻiyu miyalpeṉa moḻipa</l>
      </lg>
      <lg xml:lang="en">
<l>In the words of the second person<note place="foot"><foreign xml:lang="ta">muṉṉilai moḻi.</foreign> Accord. to Iḷam., <foreign xml:lang="ta">muṟṟu</foreign> ' completely ' implies that the above words will
          follow the previous rule only after receiving the <foreign xml:lang="ta">-u,</foreign> and that, hence, both <foreign xml:lang="ta">kauvukoṟṟā</foreign> and <foreign xml:lang="ta">kauvukkoṟṟā</foreign> is
          possible, as well as e.g. <foreign xml:lang="ta">uriñukoṟṟā</foreign> and <foreign xml:lang="ta">uriñukkoṟṟā ;</foreign> the other 2. p. forms mentioned are <foreign xml:lang="ta">porun, tirun, tevvu</foreign> and <foreign xml:lang="ta">kūṭu.</foreign></note></l>
<l>ending in the vowel <foreign xml:lang="ta">au</foreign> and in the non-vocalised</l>
<l>consonants <foreign xml:lang="ta">ñ, n, m, v,</foreign></l>
<l>and when the over-shot <foreign xml:lang="ta">u</foreign> occurs at the end,</l>
<l>[the above-said rule ?] does not apply completely.</l>

      </lg>
    </div>
